    "author_association": "MEMBER",
    "body": "Most opcodes increment the program counter (`pc`) by one. The only exceptions are:\r\n\r\n - Jump Instructions (`jumpi`, `jump`)\r\n - Push Instructions (`push1`, `push2`, ...)\r\n\r\nBefore #273 the interpreter main loop [incremented `pc` after each instruction](https://github.com/ethereum/eth1.0-specs/blob/68d5d604743bb4d1659b1e1fedc405fcf04c07fa/src/ethereum/frontier/vm/interpreter.py#L96). After #273, the interpreter [conditionally increments](https://github.com/ethereum/eth1.0-specs/blob/7c82e7a02f10e1a789911acf6de8343a8dae17cc/src/ethereum/frontier/vm/interpreter.py#L104) `pc` based on a list of instructions.\r\n\r\nI would prefer to see each opcode increment `pc` within its implementation function. So most opcodes (ex. `add`) would simply `evm.pc += 1`, but pushes can account for their length, and jumps can just set `pc` directly.",
